## The Regulatory Framework Most People Never See

What catches most wheelchair users off guard is that transportation accessibility requirements vary dramatically based on company size, service type, and regulatory classification. Companies operating fewer than 5 vehicles often qualify for ADA exemptions that allow modified compliance standards rather than full accessibility requirements.

According to [Department of Transportation accessibility regulations](https://www.transportation.gov/civil-rights/ada), private transportation companies serving the general public must provide equivalent service to passengers with disabilities, but the specific requirements depend on whether they're classified as public transportation, private charter services, or specialized medical transport.

The compliance gap becomes obvious when you examine vehicle specifications. True ADA compliance requires wheelchair positions that accommodate wheelchairs up to 30 inches wide and 48 inches long, with securement systems rated for specific crash test standards. Many companies operating "accessible" vehicles use equipment that meets only basic transport standards without full ADA specification compliance.

